    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-18T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-18T09:00:00-05:00" n="945"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d945">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00118 European War 1939/417: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]<note n="12" xml:id="d945fn12">The remainder
                            of this telegram is printed on <ref target="#pg_901">p. 901</ref>, where
                            the last two sentences are concerned with the present whereabouts of Dr.
                            Devenis.</note>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-18T17:00:00+03:00"
                            >July 18, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 6:06 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1374. In the course of a conversation with Lozovski this afternoon:</p>
                <p>1. He frankly admitted that the delay in granting exit visas to Mrs. Habicht and
                    Mrs. Magidoff was due to the fact that he was “awaiting action in the Ovakimian
                    and Bookkniga cases.” I told him that these cases are receiving the attention of
                    the Department and probably will be disposed of in the near future and invited
                    his attention to the fact that Gorin had been released and allowed to depart
                    from the United States before Roszkowski and Pyk had been freed from
                    imprisonment. I also pointed out that the time element was of greater importance
                    in Moscow than in Washington at present. After further discussion he agreed to
                    authorize issuance of exit visas for Mrs. Habicht and Mrs. Magidoff tomorrow
                    saying that he would assume that Ovakimian and Bookkniga cases would be
                    favorably acted upon without too great delay.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
